ity: Conclusion and Future Implications -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aGender-based violence (GBV) can take many forms and have detrimental effects across generations and cultures. The triangulation of GBV, rurality and rural culture is a challenging and essential topic and this edited collection provides an innovative analysis of GBV in rural communities. Focusing on under-studied and/or oppressed groups such as immigrants and LGBT+ people, the book explores new theories on patterns of violence. Giving insights into GBV education and prevention, the text introduces community justice and victim advocacy approaches to tackling issues of GBV in rural areas. From policy review into actionable change, the editors examine best practices to positively affect the lives of survivors.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aGender-based violence. 0aRural conditions. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Criminology.2bisacsh1 aAlexander AbiNader, Millan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAllen, Sam, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBainter, Madison, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBarrick, Kelle, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBlackburn, Kaiti, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrungardt, Christie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCampbell, Julia K., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDeKeseredy, Walter S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEdwards, Mari-Esther, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFarrington, Jennifer, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/